TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Affect-Based Model of Recipients’ Responses to Organizational Change Events
AU  - Oreg, Shaul
AU  - Bartunek, Jean M.
AU  - Lee, Gayoung
AU  - Do, Boram
Y1  - 2016/06/22
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2018/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2014.0335
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2014.0335
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 65
EP  - 86
VL  - 43
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Following a long period during which scholarly attention was paid predominantly to the role of change agents in organizational change, change recipients and their experiences have finally begun to take center stage. Yet the typical view of recipients has been as passive reactors to change. In this article we take steps toward highlighting the central, active roles change recipients play in organizational change events. We discuss and distinguish between dimensions of valence and activation and introduce a circumplex of recipients? affective and behavioral responses to change events. We describe the primary and secondary appraisal processes through which each response type emerges and discuss outcomes of each response type. We use our model to explain how change context and process variables affect recipients? responses to change. Finally, we discuss implications of our model for theory, research, and practice.
AB  - Following a long period during which scholarly attention was paid predominantly to the role of change agents in organizational change, change recipients and their experiences have finally begun to take center stage. Yet the typical view of recipients has been as passive reactors to change. In this article we take steps toward highlighting the central, active roles change recipients play in organizational change events. We discuss and distinguish between dimensions of valence and activation and introduce a circumplex of recipients? affective and behavioral responses to change events. We describe the primary and secondary appraisal processes through which each response type emerges and discuss outcomes of each response type. We use our model to explain how change context and process variables affect recipients? responses to change. Finally, we discuss implications of our model for theory, research, and practice.
